PRD — Backfill Shifts

Product name: Backfill Shifts
Internal codename: Schedule Mode
Status: Draft v1
Owner: Cardin / Product
Primary audience: Product, design, engineering, GTM
North star: Every customer that finishes onboarding leaves with a usable, durable operating mode inside Backfill—either by connecting an existing scheduler or by running directly on Backfill Shifts.

1. Executive summary

Backfill Shifts is a lightweight, text-first scheduling and coverage layer for hourly-work businesses. It exists for two reasons:

to activate customers who do not already use a dedicated scheduler, and
to become the preferred operating mode for customers who value speed, simplicity, and native coverage automation more than a heavyweight workforce suite.

This is not a fallback-only product. It must be designed as if some customers will never connect Deputy, Homebase, When I Work, or another scheduler. That means Backfill’s roster, schedule history, publish states, shift changes, and coverage updates must be durable enough to function as a real system of record for day-to-day operations.

The product thesis is:

AI drafts the schedule. Managers control it by text. The website is for visual review and exception handling. Backfill then handles callouts and coverage natively.

1.1 Implementation constraints from the current codebase

The product direction is right, but engineering should anchor it to the system that already exists:

* Backfill already runs on FastAPI + SQLite + Next.js with real operational tables for `organizations`, `locations`, `workers`, `shifts`, `cascades`, `outreach_attempts`, `audit_log`, `onboarding_sessions`, `integration_events`, `sync_jobs`, and `retell_conversations`.
* There is already a live coverage engine. Backfill Shifts should extend that engine and write back into the same operational ledger, not introduce a second parallel coverage system first.
* The current web app does not have a real manager auth / RBAC system yet. v1 should assume the existing internal/admin-style access model and manager phone identity remain the control surface unless auth becomes a hard requirement.
* The onboarding fork into scheduler connect vs. Backfill Shifts has already been started in code. What remains is the durable schedule layer, import pipeline, publish flow, and schedule-aware coverage behavior.
* The biggest architectural gap today is that Backfill can store shifts, but it cannot yet represent a durable published schedule with assigned employees, versions, and amendments. That is the real v1 foundation.

This direction is supported by the current scheduling market: Microsoft Shifts supports creating schedules, importing from Excel, copying schedules, and sharing them with teams; Homebase emphasizes reusable schedules, conflict alerts, and editing before or after publishing; Deputy auto-creates schedules from agreed hours that managers then publish; and When I Work supports copying prior schedules and recurring/repeating shifts. Those patterns validate that “draft → review → publish” and “copy last week” are table stakes, while also leaving room for a narrower, text-native experience.

2. Problem

A meaningful segment of Backfill’s target market either:

has no scheduler,
has an inconsistent spreadsheet/whiteboard workflow,
or has a scheduler that is too heavyweight relative to how they actually run the business.

Without a source of truth for who is working, when they are working, and who is eligible to cover, Backfill can onboard an account but still fail to activate the customer operationally.

Today, that creates three failure modes:

CSV customers upload data once but have nothing durable to operate from next week.
Managers still need a second system to create and publish schedules.
Coverage automation is weakened because Backfill lacks a live schedule record to update when reality changes.
3. Strategic decision

Backfill Shifts will be built as a primary-capable operating mode, not a disposable onboarding shim.

That changes the bar for v1:

roster CRUD is mandatory,
schedule lifecycle states are mandatory,
“copy last week” is mandatory,
employee messaging consent/onboarding is mandatory,
post-publish amendments are mandatory,
coverage outcomes must write back into the schedule record.

The core product question for every v1 feature is:

Does this work if the customer never connects a scheduler?

If the answer is no, either fix the design or mark it as an explicit v1 gap.

4. Goals
Primary goals
Activate scheduler-less customers by the end of onboarding.
Let a manager publish a usable schedule within the same onboarding session or shortly after.
Make Backfill usable week after week without requiring repeated CSV uploads.
Make callouts and open-shift coverage update the same schedule system customers rely on operationally.
Keep the manager’s primary control surface in SMS, with the web as a visual aid for complexity.
Secondary goals
Reduce manager time spent creating and revising schedules.
Improve fill rates by using schedule-aware eligibility.
Increase customer retention by making “approve next week” easier than using a traditional scheduler.
Create a path where some customers choose Backfill Shifts instead of integrating a third-party scheduler.
5. Non-goals

Backfill Shifts v1 will not include:

payroll
time clock / time and attendance
recruiting / hiring
HRIS / employee file storage
deep labor forecasting
deep compliance coverage across all jurisdictions
POS-native labor optimization
benefits or document workflows

This keeps the product narrow and aligned with the wedge: scheduling, schedule communication, callouts, and coverage.

6. Product positioning

What Backfill Shifts is:
A lightweight scheduling and coverage operating mode for hourly-work teams.

What it is not:
A full workforce-management suite.

Positioning statement:
“If you already have a scheduler, Backfill connects to it. If you don’t, Backfill Shifts gives you the fastest way to publish schedules, handle callouts, and fill coverage gaps—without adopting a bloated workforce stack.”

