11. Core use cases
Use case A: no scheduler, CSV available

Manager uploads CSV of employees and shifts, reviews mapping, fixes errors, publishes first schedule, invites employees to enroll, and starts using Backfill for callouts and coverage.

Use case B: no scheduler, no clean CSV

Manager uses guided setup to create roster and initial shifts, then uses copy/reuse for future weeks.

Use case C: recurring weekly operation

Manager receives a text that next week’s draft is ready, reviews summary, approves by text, and only opens the site if there are conflicts.

Use case D: same-day callout

Employee texts Backfill that they cannot work. Backfill marks shift at risk/open, notifies eligible employees, routes claims, and updates the schedule once filled or escalated.

12. Functional requirements
12.1 Onboarding fork

At the end of customer onboarding:

if supported scheduler exists, offer scheduler connection;
otherwise route into Backfill Shifts.

The customer must leave onboarding with one of:

live integration connected, or
first schedule imported/drafted in Backfill Shifts.
12.2 CSV import

Manager can:

download a template,
upload CSV,
choose import type:
roster only
shifts only
combined roster + shifts
map source columns to Backfill fields,
preview rows before commit,
save a mapping profile per location.

Microsoft Shifts’ Excel-import pattern validates the template-upload-import mental model; Backfill should borrow that ergonomics layer without copying the full Microsoft product.

Required roster fields
