12.3 Conversational import for small teams

For very small teams, Backfill may offer a guided phone/text path that captures:

business/location,
number of employees,
employee names and phone numbers,
recurring shift patterns.

This is not the default for larger teams. CSV remains a primary onboarding path, not just a power-user path.

12.4 Partial import and error recovery

Imports can succeed partially.

Fatal errors

Import blocks entirely if:

required columns cannot be mapped,
file is unreadable,
date/time parsing fails for a majority of rows,
location context is missing when required.
Non-fatal errors

Import proceeds with warnings if:

some employees are missing emails,
some phone numbers are malformed,
some rows have unknown roles,
some shifts are missing assignees and can be converted to open shifts.

Bad rows go to an Action Needed queue. Manager can:

fix inline,
download error CSV,
ignore rows temporarily,
complete import and return later.
12.5 Roster CRUD

Manager/admin must be able to:

add employee
edit employee
deactivate employee
reactivate employee
transfer employee between locations
update role eligibility
update phone/email
mark enrollment status
mark employee unavailable / inactive / terminated

This is mandatory because Backfill Shifts is being designed as a primary-capable mode, not just a bridge.

12.6 Schedule creation methods

Backfill Shifts supports four ways to create a schedule:

import existing shifts by CSV
copy last published week
apply recurring shift patterns/templates
generate AI draft from history, roles, availability, and rules

Current products treat copy/reuse and repeat patterns as standard manager behavior, so Backfill must support reuse from the start. Microsoft Shifts supports copying schedules, and When I Work supports copying previous schedules and repeating shifts.

12.7 AI schedule drafting

The draft engine should consider:

prior published schedules
employee roles and secondary roles
location eligibility
availability
approved time off
max weekly hours
minimum rest buffer
simple fairness rules
manager-set priorities
open required shifts
overtime guardrails where configured

This follows the established “auto-create, then publish once satisfied” pattern seen in Deputy and the editable/reusable schedule flow in Homebase.

12.8 Schedule lifecycle states

Every schedule lives in one of these states:

Draft — editable, not visible to employees
Published — current version shared with employees
Amended — published schedule with approved changes after publish
Archived — historical, read-only except for audit/admin actions
Recalled — previously published date range temporarily pulled back for revision
State rules
Only draft schedules can be bulk-rewritten without notification.
Publishing creates a versioned snapshot.
Changes to a published schedule create amendment records.
Amendments trigger notifications based on change type.
Archived schedules remain queryable for history, analytics, and future drafting.

Microsoft Shifts’ create/share/copy model supports the need for explicit publish states rather than treating schedules as a single mutable blob.

12.9 Manager approval by SMS

Managers should be able to approve most schedules by text.

Example:

Backfill: Your Apr 13–19 draft is ready. 42 of 46 shifts are assigned. 2 need review: 1 overtime risk, 1 unfilled closer on Fri. Reply APPROVE or tap to review.

Supported actions:

APPROVE
REVIEW
FIX
COPY LAST WEEK
PUBLISH
HOLD
HELP

Text should summarize exceptions narratively before forcing a web visit.

12.10 Website review experience

The site should emphasize exceptions, not spreadsheet admin.

Primary views:

weekly schedule grid
unfilled shifts
conflicts
overtime risk
unavailable assignment risk
missing employee enrollment
recommended swaps/fixes

The grid should exist because some problems are spatial and easier to resolve visually, but the site should be purpose-built for review and exception handling rather than becoming a bloated workforce UI.

12.11 Employee schedule delivery

Once published:

employees receive schedule notifications by their consented channel,
managers receive confirmation of publish,
the schedule becomes the active source of truth.

Suggested weekly employee message:

Backfill for [Business]: Your week is Mon 9–5, Wed 11–7, Fri 6–close. Reply ? for questions.

12.12 Employee enrollment and consent

Employee phone numbers imported by manager/scheduler/CSV do not equal consent for recurring Backfill messaging. Twilio requires consent from the message recipient before the first message, records of that consent, and clarity on what type of messages the recipient agreed to receive. CTIA guidance also recommends a confirmation message for recurring programs that includes program identity and opt-out instructions.

Enrollment model
manager onboarding creates roster only
manager invites employees to enroll using trusted employer channels
employees self-enroll from their own phone, QR flow, or web consent flow
Backfill sends enrollment confirmation
only then does recurring messaging begin
Enrollment states
not invited
invited
opted in
opted out
help requested
blocked/unreachable
12.13 Opt-out handling

Backfill must support standard opt-out behavior and track opt-in/opt-out/help events. Twilio Messaging Services support standard STOP-style keywords, maintain a block list for opted-out users, and on U.S. toll-free numbers only START and UNSTOP fully reverse blocking after STOP.

12.14 Callout workflow

Employee texts:

“I can’t make my shift tonight”

System behavior:

identify active or upcoming matching shift
mark shift “at risk” or “open pending review”
notify manager if configured
start coverage logic
send offers to eligible employees
update schedule when filled, declined, or escalated
12.15 Open-shift workflow

For open or newly-open shifts:

determine eligibility by role/location/status/availability
apply manager rules on send order
send text offers
capture claim responses
auto-assign or require manager approval based on rules
write result back into schedule history
12.16 Schedule amendment workflow

If a published shift changes:

change is recorded as amendment
affected employee is notified
manager sees confirmation
audit log captures who changed what and when
